lopment, and ecological contamination. In so doing, she proposes that postwar zones are their own cultural and area studies, offering new ways to understand the parallel relationship between ongoing war violence and postwar revival.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aCluster bombszLaos. 0aEthnologyzLaos. 0aLand mine victimszLaos. 0aUnexploded ordnancexSocial aspectszLaos. 0aVietnam War, 1961-1975xAerial operations, American. 0aVietnam War, 1961-1975xCampaignszLaos. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2019z978311069632540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478005261zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478005261423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478005261.jpg  a978-3-11-069632-5  DUK eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles